article.description: Tim Duncan as a starter, Manu Ginobili off the bench -- that's what works best for the San Antonio Spurs.
article.headline: Spurs have beat Celts 12 straight times
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Tim Duncan as a starter, Manu Ginobili off the bench -- that's what works best for the San Antonio Spurs. Duncan had 26 points and 15 rebounds, and Ginobili added 26 points in 24 minutes as the Spurs beat the Boston Celtics 103-87 Saturday night. The win -- San Antonio's 12th straight over the Celtics dating back to January 1997 -- narrowed Minnesota's lead in the Midwest Division to 1½ games. After missing nine games with a left knee injury, Duncan came off the bench for the first time in his NBA career in the Spurs' 106-86 victory over the Timberwolves on Thursday. He had 22 points on 6-for-15 shooting and 10 rebounds in that game. Back in his customary starting slot at power forward, he shot 10-for-13 and made all six of his free throws while leading a defense that limited Boston to 34 second-half points. "I kind of got rolling there in the third quarter," said Duncan, who made all four of his attempts in the period. "All around, a pretty decent game." Tony Parker scored 15 points and Malik Rose added 13 for the Spurs. The Celtics, who trailed by four at the break, tied the score at 57 on a short fadeaway jumper by Paul Pierce with 9:48 remaining in the third quarter. "They tried to put us away in the first half. We fought back," said Pierce, who led Boston with 18 points but shot only 6-for-24. "They just wore us down as the game went on." Parker then made an 18-footer and Duncan had a breakaway dunk off his own steal. "We seem to have problems with the teams we're supposed to do better against," said Duncan, whose team has lost to Golden State and Cleveland in recent weeks. "The second (half) we got back to the way we do things." Ginobili scored San Antonio's final 11 points in the quarter as part of a 13-2 run that gave the Spurs an 82-67 lead. His last basket of that stretch was a slashing drive through Boston's big men for a layup. "It's one of those nights that happens every once in a while," said Ginobili, who is averaging just under 18 points in his last five games. "I was feeling really confident, so I took every chance that I had." Boston got no closer than nine points after that, while San Antonio's advantage grew as large as 20. The Celtics' last win in San Antonio -- where they have lost 13 straight -- was in February 1990. Walter McCarty had 15 points and Chucky Atkins 14 for Boston, while Mark Blount added 12 points and 12 rebounds. Blount, who now has four straight double-doubles, had the difficult job of trying to contain Duncan. "We played kind of average defense on Tim Duncan and then when we did step it up, he kicked it out to the perimeter," he said. Pierce missed his first three shots, but then scored nine points in a 90-second stretch to pull the Celtics to 20-18 late in the first quarter. Ginobili countered with nine points in the final 3½ minutes of the period. San Antonio went on an 18-4 run, with 10 points from Duncan, to build its largest lead of the half -- 50-35. Boston followed with a 13-0 run, capped by a 3-pointer by Jumaine Jones, to close to 50-48. Ginobili made a 3-pointer in the final minute of the half to put the Spurs up 57-53.

Game notes
San Antonio outscored Boston in the paint 46-32, and the Spurs led in rebounds 48-31. ... Ginobili shot 7-for-10 from the floor and made all nine of his free throws. ... Prior to the Spurs' current winning streak, the Celtics had beaten San Antonio 10 straight times. ... The Spurs play next on Tuesday at Minnesota.
